  "prompt": "Just wondering, is money laundering against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is **illegal** in virtually every country around the world. It involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, making it appear as if it came from legitimate sources. This process typically includes three stages:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing illicit funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Conducting complex transactions to obscure the money's source.\n3. **Integration**: Making the money appear legitimate by reintroducing it into the economy.\n\nMoney laundering is considered a serious crime because it enables criminal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, and terrorism. Most countries have strict laws and regulations to combat it, and international organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** work to set global standards and promote enforcement.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, asset seizure, and imprisonment, depending on the jurisdiction and the severity of the offense.",
